When data is transmitted across a network, it is broken into smaller pieces to make communication more efficient. Two important units of data are packets and frames.
Although they carry the same information, they operate at different layers of the OSI Model.

Packets:
A packet is the unit of data used at the Network Layer (Layer 3).

A packet contains:

Source IP address
Destination IP address
Data payload

Routers use packet information to determine where data should be sent across networks.

Frames:
A frame is the unit of data used at the Data Link Layer (Layer 2).

A frame contains:

Source MAC address
Destination MAC address
Data payload

Switches use frames to deliver data between devices on the same local network.

How do they work together?

When data is sent across a network:

Data is placed into a packet with IP addressing information.
The packet is then encapsulated into a frame containing MAC addresses.
The frame is transmitted across the local network.
Routers use the packet information to forward traffic between networks.

Packet VS Frame
Packet - Layer 3 (Network); Uses IP addresses; Routed between networks
Frame - Layer 2 (Data Link); Uses MAC addresses; Delivered within local networks

Why It Matters:
Understanding packets and frames helps explain how devices communicate and how network traffic is analyzed during troubleshooting and security investigations.

Key Takeaways:
Data is transmitted across networks in small units.
Packets operate at Layer 3 and use IP addresses.
Frames operate at Layer 2 and use MAC addresses.
Packets are routed between networks, while frames are used within local networks.
